.Pp
I invest quite a bit of time in maintaining my Nix config, so naturally, I
often find myself trying to answer the question, for interested and/or
concerned friends and family members, "What's the point of it?".
.Pp
It's difficult to explain because my use of Nix is considerably broad.
Primarily, it's architecture-as-code for my homelab servers and Hetzner VPSes,
which is already difficult to explain to a layperson. It's purpose in that
regard is as an abstraction layer to make self-hosting various web services and
game servers more convenient.
.Pp
But I also use it to manage my personal machines, such as the Linux partition
of my x86 desktop computer, or my Macbook Air with nix-darwin. Nix is an
amazing piece of software that fundamentally changes how you are able to manage
computer systems. 
.Pp
In this post, I'll go over things I've been doing with Nix over the last ~14
months, what I've learned along the way, and the techniques I've discovered to
take full advantage of the capability of Nix and NixOS.
.Sh What is Nix?
If you're already familiar with Nix and NixOS, you may skip this section. Note,
my explanations here will assume a background of working with Linux systems. If
you're new to Linux and would like to get into it, I can recommend [TODO] as a
starting point.
.Pp
It's not fully correct to describe Nix as a piece of software. Rather, it is a
collection of things. First and foremost, Nix is a functional programming
language, like Elixir or Haskell, as opposed to a procedural programming
language, such as...most programming languages today. Java, C#, JavaScript,
C/C++ and Swift are all examples of procedural programming languages.
.Pp
A procedural programming language describes, at a high level, the instructions
that the computer should execute. Take the below example of a C program.
.Bd -literal
__POSTPROCESS(@chroma@ -l c)
@include:fibonacci.c@
__END
.Ed
You can run this program like so.
.Bd -literal
__POSTPROCESS(@chroma@ -l bash)
$ gcc fibonacci.c -o fibonacci
$ ./fibonacci 23
$ # ==> __PREPROCESS(gcc -x c - -o fibonacci && ./fibonacci 23)
@include:fibonacci.c@
__END
__END
.Ed
.Pp
Procedural programming languages are so popular because they are such a great
way to implement many classes of software. However, some problems are better
suited to functional programming languages. 
.
Here is an implementation of the same program in Haskell, a functional language.
.Bd -literal
__POSTPROCESS(@chroma@ -l haskell)
@include:fibonacci.hs@
__END
.Ed
Similarly, you can run the program like this.
.Bd -literal
__POSTPROCESS(@chroma@ -l bash)
$ ghc fibonacci.hs -o fibonacci
$ ./fibonacci 23
$ # ==> __PREPROCESS(ghc --frontend GhcStdin -ffrontend-opt "-o fibonacci" &>/dev/null && ./fibonacci 23)
@include:fibonacci.hs@
__END
__END
.Ed
